<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-745-786  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 745 786.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 13 1990 v24 n33 p61(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Storage technologies: putting data in its proper place.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Radding, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Data storage managers have a number of options, both tried andtrue devices and new technologies, that merit consideration whenchoosing the most appropriate storage device.andP;  Traditionaldirect-access storage devices (DASD) are not always the mostsuited to a particular task.andP;  New technologies include redundantarrays of inexpensive disks (RAID) and extended or cache memory.andO;The newer types of storage systems add a new dimension to thestorage hierarchy.andP;  This dimension is called 'in-line' and'near-line' storage.andP;  In-line storage includes random accessmemory (RAM) disks, solid-state disks and disk cache.andP;  Near-linestorage is available either as automated tape libraries (ATL) oroptical-disc jukeboxes, both forms combine storage media withrobotics.andP;  Currently only DASD provides on-line storage, but RAIDmay soon offer some competition.andP;  A buyer's guide on solid-statedisks and disk emulators is included.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Storage HierarchiesDirect Access Storage DevicesRAMOptical DisksMagnetic disksPerformance-Cost RelationshipStorage MediaDirectories.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   The traditional storage hierarchy has become more complex. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>